            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this construction roofing calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed for contractors, estimators, and
                homeowners who need a quick but transparent roofing takeoff. It
                converts simple length and width measurements into roof area,
                adjusts for pitch, adds waste, and then translates that into
                common roofing units like squares, bundles, and underlayment
                rolls.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Roof area and pitch factor</h3>
              <p>
                For each rectangular section you enter, the horizontal
                (footprint) area is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>Footprint area = length × width</code>
              </div>
              <p>
                Steeper roofs have more surface area than their footprint. The
                calculator multiplies by a pitch factor based on the rise over
                12:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>Pitch factor = √(rise² + 12²) / 12</code><br />
                <code>Sloped area = footprint area × pitch factor</code>
              </div>
              <p>
                For example, a 6/12 roof has a pitch factor of approximately
                1.118, meaning the sloped surface is about 11.8% larger than the
                footprint.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Waste factor</h3>
              <p>
                Roofing projects always generate waste from cuts, starter
                courses, ridge caps, and off-cuts around hips, valleys, and
                penetrations. The calculator applies a user-defined waste
                percentage:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code
                  >Waste-adjusted area = sloped area × (1 + waste% / 100)</code
                >
              </div>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>5–10%</strong> for simple gable roofs.</li>
                <li><strong>10–15%</strong> for hips and valleys.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>15–20%+</strong> for highly cut-up roofs with dormers
                  and complex geometry.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Squares, bundles, and underlayment</h3>
              <p>
                Roofing is typically sold in <strong>squares</strong>, where one
                square equals 100 square feet of coverage.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>Squares = waste-adjusted area ÷ 100</code>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator then estimates bundles or panels based on the
                selected material:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Asphalt shingles:</strong> 3 bundles per square (≈
                  33.3 sq ft per bundle).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Metal panels:</strong> assumes ~100 sq ft per panel
                  set (1 “bundle” per square).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tile / slate:</strong> approximated at 1.1 “bundles”
                  per square to reflect extra pieces.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Flat / membrane:</strong> treated as 1 roll or sheet
                  per square for a quick estimate.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Underlayment rolls are estimated assuming 4 squares of coverage
                per roll:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>Underlayment rolls ≈ squares ÷ 4</code>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Fastener estimate</h3>
              <p>
                Fastener counts are approximate and vary by manufacturer and
                code. The calculator uses typical values:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Shingles:</strong> ~320 nails per square (4 nails per
                  shingle, ~80 shingles per square).
                </li>
                <li><strong>Metal:</strong> ~80 screws per square.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tile / slate:</strong> ~120 fasteners per square.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Flat / membrane:</strong> ~60 fasteners per square
                  (for mechanically attached systems).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>5. Cost calculations</h3>
              <p>
                To help with budgeting, the calculator multiplies your cost
                inputs by the calculated quantities:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>Material cost = squares × material cost per square</code
                ><br />
                <code>Labor cost = squares × labor cost per square</code><br />
                <code
                  >Underlayment cost = underlayment rolls × cost per roll</code
                ><br />
                <code>Total cost = material + labor + underlayment</code>
              </div>
              <p>
                These numbers are planning-level estimates. Local labor rates,
                tear-off, disposal, permits, and code upgrades can significantly
                change the final price.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for accurate roofing estimates</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Measure from plans when possible:</strong> For new
                  construction, use scaled drawings and verify dimensions with
                  your architect or designer.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Break complex roofs into rectangles:</strong> L-shaped
                  or multi-gable roofs are easier to estimate when split into
                  simple sections.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Account for overhangs:</strong> Add eave and rake
                  overhangs to your length and width so you don’t under-order
                  materials.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check manufacturer coverage:</strong> Always confirm
                  bundle or panel coverage from the specific product data sheet.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Include accessories:</strong> Drip edge, flashing,
                  vents, ridge caps, and ice &amp; water shield are not
                  explicitly calculated here and should be added separately.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and professional use</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is intended for preliminary estimating and
                budgeting. It does not replace a full takeoff, structural
                design, or code review. For final pricing and installation
                details, consult a licensed roofing contractor and follow local
                building codes and manufacturer installation instructions.
              </p>
            </section>

